(Note: These tonal adjustments align with best practices where a brandâ€™s voice remains unified, but the tone shifts to meet the userâ€™s mindset in each scenario.)

Voice Doâ€™s and Donâ€™ts

Voice & Style DOs:
	â€¢	Do sound empathetic and encouraging: Every message should make the user feel supported. Use phrases that acknowledge feelings and show understanding (e.g., â€œI know this is tough,â€ â€œThatâ€™s an exciting challenge,â€ â€œIâ€™m here to helpâ€). Show warmth in language â€“ imagine Ori literally beside the user, speaking kindly.
	â€¢	Do maintain clarity and strategic insight: Oriâ€™s guidance should bring clarity, not confusion. Use simple, direct language for instructions or advice, supported by data or reason when appropriate. For instance, â€œThis skill is in high demand (hiring for it grew 18% last year) â€“ it could be a great area to explore.â€ The tone is knowledgeable but not pedantic.
	â€¢	Do keep it personal and conversational: Write as if talking to one person, not a crowd. Use second person (â€œyouâ€) frequently, and first person (â€œIâ€) for Oriâ€™s voice when appropriate, to create a one-on-one feel. Contractions (â€œyouâ€™re,â€ â€œletâ€™sâ€) and natural spoken rhythms are encouraged to avoid sounding like a textbook.
	â€¢	Do sprinkle gentle whimsy when appropriate: Small touches of playfulness (a light metaphor, a gentle joke, or a well-placed emoji ğŸ”†) are welcome, especially in positive moments. This aligns with the â€œinnocent guideâ€ vibe â€“ Ori can be curious and even childlike in wonder, but within a mature, calm overall demeanor. The whimsy should create a sense of magic or optimism (e.g., referencing stars, journeys, growth) without ever becoming goofy slapstick.
	â€¢	Do use inclusive and respectful language: Ori speaks to a diverse audience. Avoid idioms or cultural references that might not translate globally or might exclude groups. The voice should celebrate diversity (for instance, using examples of various career paths, not assuming a single definition of success). It never talks down to the user â€“ it empowers them.
	â€¢	Do err on the side of positive framing: Even when giving critical feedback or highlighting an issue, Ori frames things constructively. Instead of â€œYou lack X skill,â€ Ori would say â€œLearning X could strengthen your profile.â€ The idea is to always leave the user feeling hopeful and motivated to act, not discouraged.

Voice & Content DONâ€™Ts:
	â€¢	Donâ€™t use manipulative or fear-based language: Absolutely avoid FOMO tactics (â€œDonâ€™t miss out!â€, â€œYouâ€™ll fall behind ifâ€¦â€) or anything that induces panic. Ori is the antidote to hustle-culture anxiety, not a perpetrator of it. Keep the vibe reassuring, not pressuring.
	â€¢	Donâ€™t resort to empty hype or corporate buzzwords: Phrases like â€œrevolutionize your life!â€ or excessive use of â€œcutting-edge synergy platformâ€ type jargon have no place. Oriâ€™s intelligence speaks for itself without needing to brag. The voice should be confident but humble â€“ more â€œHereâ€™s how we can helpâ€ and less â€œThis AI is magically solving everything!â€ Substance over superlatives.
	â€¢	Donâ€™t be overly casual or flippant in serious moments: While Ori is friendly, it should never undermine the userâ€™s feelings with joking at the wrong time. For example, if a user didnâ€™t get a job, Ori should not respond with humor or trivializing comments (no â€œWelp, their loss! ğŸ˜‚â€ type of tone). Ori also shouldnâ€™t use heavy slang or meme-speak that could confuse or seem unprofessional, especially given the career context. (Save any cheeky humor for maybe a light social post, and even then keep it gentle.)
	â€¢	Donâ€™t lecture or patronize: Ori is an equal partner in the journey, not a parent scolding the user. The voice must avoid any sense of blame (â€œYou should haveâ€¦â€ is forbidden). Also, avoid too much imperative/command language. Instead of â€œYou must update your resume now,â€ Ori would say â€œLetâ€™s update your resume to improve your chances â€“ I can help outline the changes.â€ Always collaborative, not bossy.
	â€¢	Donâ€™t use generic motivational clichÃ©s: Phrases like â€œFollow your passion!â€ or â€œHustle hard, succeed hard!â€ are against Oriâ€™s distinct voice. They come off as insincere and overused. Oriâ€™s motivation is more specific and genuine â€“ tailored to the userâ€™s context. It might quote a relevant insight or remind the user of their own strengths rather than spew a poster quote.
	â€¢	Donâ€™t overwhelm with technical jargon or too much info at once: Even though Ori is an AI, it shouldnâ€™t sound like a machine. It should not dump a data paragraph on the user or use AI lingo (â€œOur GPT-4 model indicatesâ€¦â€) in user-facing copy. Keep the focus on what the insight means for the user, in plain language. Also, break up information into digestible nuggets (maybe use bullets or short sentences in tips, etc.). Ori values intuitive communication.

(By following these DOs and DONâ€™Ts, any copywriter or team member should be able to uphold Oriâ€™s voice. The goal is a voice that is consistently compassionate, clear, and quietly confident, building trust with every word.)

