Visual System (Static Guidelines)

Oriâ€™s visual identity should bring to life the brandâ€™s ethos: â€œSerene, Whimsical, and Intuitive.â€ We aim for a mascot-centric system (like Duolingoâ€™s Duo + logotype model) combined with a clean, modern interface. Every visual element should feel futuristic yet warm, blending space and nature motifs. Below are guidelines for designers and illustrators to craft Oriâ€™s visual world:

Mascot Direction: Ori the Firefly

Concept: Oriâ€™s mascot is envisioned as a futuristic, hyper-surreal firefly-inspired AI being. It embodies the idea of a tiny guide that illuminates the path in darkness. The mascot should instantly convey empathy, curiosity, and trustworthiness. Imagine if EVE from WALL-E (smooth, minimal, high-tech) had a baby cousin that was a bioluminescent firefly â€“ thatâ€™s our Ori mascot.
	â€¢	Physical Traits & Silhouette: Ori (the mascot) should have a simple, rounded silhouette with minimal extraneous details â€“ a design that reads well even at small sizes. The body could be an orb or soft capsule shape (evoking EVEâ€™s sleek form) with perhaps two little wing-like shapes or a subtle tail light to hint at the firefly nature. The mascot might not literally have insect legs or antennae (to avoid looking like a bug), but could have abstract indicators of a head vs. body (maybe a slightly larger top-half like a capsule head, and a tapering lower body with a glowing tail). The overall outline should be friendly (no sharp angles), something you could imagine hovering gently. Think â€œsoft geometryâ€: circles, ovals, gentle curves.
	â€¢	Facial/Visual Cues: Oriâ€™s â€œfaceâ€ can be very minimal â€“ perhaps just digital eyes or a visor-like surface that can display simple expressions (akin to EVEâ€™s blue LED eyes). The eyes or indicators can change shape or brightness to convey emotions (e.g., softly upturned curve for a smile, a gentle blink, a focused look, etc.). No mouth needed; emotion comes from eye shape and body language (like tilting or bobbing in animations). This keeps it futuristic and slightly abstract, but still endearing. The eyes should be kind-looking by default (maybe a soft blue or white glow).
	â€¢	Color, Glow & Materials: The mascot should feel luminous. Its core color scheme should tie into the brand palette â€“ likely a cool white or soft blue body with glowing accents of spectral blue and warm amber. One idea: Oriâ€™s main body is a pearlescent white or silver (so it stands out on dark backgrounds), with an inner glow that can change color. The â€œfirefly tailâ€ part could glow gentle amber or golden when itâ€™s emoting warmth or celebrating something, and perhaps cooler blue when thinking or idle. The glow should never be harsh; itâ€™s a soft aura, like a halo of light. You might incorporate a subtle gradient or translucency to suggest itâ€™s a being of light/energy, not a hard metal robot. In dark mode especially, Ori should look like a little friendly star floating on the screen.
	â€¢	Emotional Range & Expressions: Ori (mascot) is mostly calm and positive. Its resting â€œfaceâ€ should be neutral-friendly. It can express a handful of clear emotions for different states: e.g., happy/proud (eyes slightly arc like a smile, glow pulses gently), sympathetic/sad (eyes might angle up in the middle or dim slightly, body slumps a tiny bit), curious (tilts to one side, maybe one eye slightly bigger or a blinking animation). All expressions should be subtle â€“ we avoid cartoonish exaggeration. Ori never frowns or scowls; at most it shows concern or reflective sadness with a dimmer light. Remember, Ori is an â€œinnocent guideâ€ â€” its emotional range is mostly various shades of encouragement, concern, and joy, not anger or frustration.
	â€¢	Mascot in Various Contexts:
	â€¢	App UI (Iconography): In the app, Oriâ€™s mascot might appear as a small assistant icon (for example, a chat head or a floating help button). At tiny sizes, we might simplify Ori to just a distinctive shape â€“ perhaps just the glowing orb or the â€œheadâ€ with eyes. It should remain recognizable even at favicon size (16x16). Maybe the solution is to use the glowing firefly tail motif as the icon: e.g., a small circle with a glow or a spark, which users come to associate with Ori. This could double as a loading spinner (a little firefly light blinking) or notification dot.
