	â€¢	Empty States & Onboarding: In empty states, Ori can appear with an inviting gesture (maybe a subtle wing wave or just floating with a gentle bounce). For example, if an onboarding step is â€œTell us about your dream jobâ€, Ori might appear holding an abstract â€œdreamâ€ symbol (like a small star or heart) to make the screen more engaging. The illustrations here should be lightweight (not too much detail) so as not to distract â€“ possibly line art plus a bit of glow, featuring Ori next to some symbolic imagery (like a lantern, a telescope, a signpost, etc. depending on context). The key is Ori always appears as helpful, not overbearing. It might be off to the side or bottom of the illustration, leading the userâ€™s eye to the content.

(The mascot is central to brand recall, so consistency in how Ori is drawn is crucial. A style guide for the mascot should include example poses and doâ€™s/donâ€™ts â€“ e.g., Ori should always face the user or direction of travel (not show its back), Ori should never appear with angry or silly expressions that undermine trust, etc. We are creating a character that users could genuinely get attached to, much like Duolingoâ€™s owl, but in a gentler, more â€œguardian angelâ€ kind of way.)

Logo & Wordmark Guidelines

Oriâ€™s logo system will consist of a mascot logomark and a wordmark (the brand name in text). They should work in tandem but also independently.
	â€¢	Wordmark Design: The wordmark is simply the name â€œOriâ€. It should be set in a modern, clean typeface that reflects the productâ€™s personality. Think minimalistic sans-serif â€“ likely lowercase â€œoriâ€ or a capital â€œOâ€ with the rest lowercase, to give a friendly approachable vibe (all-caps might feel too loud for this brand). The letterforms should have soft, rounded touches rather than harsh geometric extremes, aligning with the humane tech feel. For example, a typeface similar to Google Sans, Avenir, or Circular could work â€“ they have a contemporary feel with circular â€˜Oâ€™ forms that echo the idea of completeness and cycles. Customization could include rounding some corners further or tweaking the â€œiâ€. Perhaps the dot on the â€œiâ€ in Ori can subtly echo the mascot (e.g., the dot could be a small colored circle that represents the firefly glow). If appropriate, the dot on the â€œiâ€ could even be abstracted as a little spark icon. The weight of the font should be medium â€“ not too light (for readability at small sizes) and not too heavy (we want an elegant, not chunky, presence).
	â€¢	Logo Mark (Mascot Integration): The mascot (Ori the firefly) itself can serve as the logo mark. We might have a simplified version of the mascot (like just the glowing orb with maybe two little wing stubs or the eyes) that can appear alongside the wordmark or standalone. A possible lockup is the mascot to the left of the text â€œOriâ€. Spacing should be such that the mascot and text feel balanced (the mascot likely roughly the cap height of the text or slightly taller). When using color, the mascot will be in full color (with its glow effects) and the text likely in a single neutral or white. For black-and-white or small scale, we might use a solid icon version of the mascot (e.g., a simple firefly outline or a circle with two wing-like shapes).
	â€¢	Combination & Separation: Ensure the logo works in these formats:
	1.	Full lockup: mascot + â€œOriâ€ wordmark for use in headers, splash screens, etc.
	2.	Wordmark alone: just â€œOriâ€ in text, e.g., for navbar when space is tight or in plain emails. This still should be recognizable given the distinct font treatment.
	3.	Mascot alone: for app favicon, social media avatar, or watermark. In those cases, the mascot icon should be distinct enough to carry brand recognition (which is why the silhouette and glow matter).
	â€¢	The brand guidelines should specify clear space around the logo. E.g., keep at least the height of the â€œOâ€ as padding on all sides when placing the full logo in a layout. The mascotâ€™s glow should not be cut off or overlapped by other elements.
	â€¢	Also consider a monochrome version: maybe the mascot can reduce to an outline or solid shape when needed (for printing in one color). The wordmark in monochrome would just be the chosen type.
	â€¢	Tone of Logo: Overall, the logo (text + mascot) should feel calm and confident. Thereâ€™s no complex graphic shape or tagline attached, just the name and the simple character. It should communicate: this is a friendly, high-tech guide. When a user sees the Ori logo on, say, a mobile app icon, it should intrigue them (glowing little creature) and reassure them (clean, professional wordmark) simultaneously.

Color Palettes

Ori will have two full color modes â€“ Dark Mode (primary experience) and Light Mode (secondary) â€“ each with a carefully chosen palette. Across both, we maintain a sense of cosmic serenity with sparing use of vibrant â€œstarâ€ colors for accents. All colors should meet accessibility standards for contrast.

Dark Mode Palette: (Primary) â€“ This is the default, where Oriâ€™s aesthetic shines (literally) like a soft glow in the dark cosmos.
	â€¢	Background & Base Darks: Instead of pure black, we use deep desaturated dark tones with a hint of color (evoking outer space). For example, a very dark navy #0D1B2A or a charcoal with blue undertone (#121212 with slight blue hue). These dark backgrounds are easier on the eyes and feel richer than flat black. We can have a couple of levels: a true background (#0D1B2A as main page background) and a slightly lighter panel color for cards or modals (#1B2635, for instance), to create layering.
	â€¢	Primary Accent (Star Blue): A bright, spectral blue that pops on the dark background. This could be akin to an electric blue or cyan-blue, e.g., #3EDBF0 (aqua) or #4F83F1 (a vibrant blue). It should feel like a piercing star or a blue flame â€“ signifying insight and action. This is used for primary buttons, links, highlights of active states. Ensure itâ€™s bright enough to have good contrast with dark base (and might often be used in its glowing form with a slight outer glow).
	â€¢	Secondary Accent (Aurora / Teal or Purple): We might incorporate a secondary color that pairs well with the blue for gradients or additional visual interest. Possibilities: a teal leaning green-blue (#80FFC2 for a neon teal) or a soft purple-indigo (#9B5CFD perhaps). The idea is a color that can appear in illustrations or gradient mixes to evoke the night sky variety (like a nebulaâ€™s hint of purple). This secondary should be used more sparingly than the primary blue.
	â€¢	Warm Accent (Amber/Red): Inspired by the idea of warmth, life, guidance â€“ we include a small dose of warm color. This could be an amber/gold (#F9A72B) or a soft red-orange (#FF7E5A). Its purpose: to highlight success states or friendly elements (maybe Oriâ€™s â€œtail lightâ€ glow uses this, or success messages get a warm tint). It should be used carefully so as not to dominate â€“ think of it as the warm lamp light in the dark. For example, maybe error messages might use a muted red derived from this (accessible red for dark mode), and success a greenish-amber. (We can derive a green as well, but likely our palette can treat amber as success to be a bit different from typical green, as long as contrast is fine.)
	â€¢	Neutrals: We need a set of neutral grays for text and secondary UI. Likely a light gray (#E0E0E0) for body text on dark (for high contrast but not stark white), a medium gray (#A0A0A0) for secondary text or labels, and an icon boundary color perhaps. White (#FFFFFF) can be used for headings or when maximum contrast is needed (e.g., white text on blue button). Essentially: white or near-white for primary text, mid-gray for secondary text, and dark gray for borders or disabled elements (e.g., #444444).
	â€¢	Semantic Colors:
	â€¢	Success could be a gentle green-blue (to stay in theme) or the amber if we choose that to highlight positive (but ensure itâ€™s not confused with warning; maybe a slightly more green tone like #3EE8A0 for success, giving a fresh alive feel on dark).
	â€¢	Warning could use the amber base (#F9A72B) in more saturation.
	â€¢	Error should be a clear but not eye-searing red (#FF5E5E maybe, which on dark is vivid but readable).
	â€¢	Info can default to the primary blue.
These should all be tested for contrast against backgrounds. The blue likely covers info and general interactive, which is fine since Oriâ€™s brand is that blue. The green (if used) should still visually fit (perhaps a teal-green that doesnâ€™t clash with blue).
	â€¢	Gradients & Glow: In dark mode, gradients featuring our accent colors can be used for special backgrounds or illustrations (e.g., a gradient of deep indigo to blue to teal to mimic a nebula). Also, using outer glows (semi-transparent blurs of accent colors) around elements like the mascot or certain buttons can reinforce the luminous theme. But use these effects deliberately â€“ for key focus points, not everywhere.

Dark mode should evoke standing under a starry sky: mostly deep blue-black, with specks of light and gentle color appears like the Milky Way. It must always remain easy to read (hence lots of contrast for text) and not devolve into neon overload. Restraint is key â€“ pops of color on a canvas of night.

Light Mode Palette: (Secondary) â€“ The light mode provides an airy, day-time counterpart to Oriâ€™s experience, while maintaining brand consistency.
	â€¢	Background & Base Lights: Use off-whites or very light cool grays instead of pure white, to avoid eye strain and to hint at a â€œmorning mistâ€ rather than sterile white. For example, #F5F7FA could be a page background (a very light gray with maybe a tiny blue hue), and #FFFFFF can still be used for cards on a slightly tinted backdrop if needed (or vice versa, white main background and a very light gray card for depth). Key is keeping it calm, not blinding.
	â€¢	Primary Accent (Star Blue): The same blue from dark mode (#3EDBF0 or similar) will be used in light mode, but we have to ensure it has enough contrast against light bg for things like text or small elements. We may need to use a slightly darker variant of it for text on white (e.g., #127D99 as a darkened version of that cyan). Or we outline icons in that color. Essentially, in light mode, the vibrant blue might appear a bit less neon due to contrast needs â€“ but should visually appear as the same â€œfamilyâ€ of blue (maybe 1-2 shades deeper).
	â€¢	Secondary & Warm Accents: Again, the teal or purple secondary can be used in graphics or as subtle fills, but should be adjusted for light mode (perhaps slightly less saturation or more contrast as needed). The warm amber can still be used for highlights (maybe as a small mark or icon color), but on white backgrounds it might need to be a bit richer to be legible (e.g., #E57C2B for amber on white). We should also define a distinct link or hover color â€“ likely the primary blue is fine for links, with maybe an underline. Hover states could use a lighter tint or subtle background fill of blue at 10% opacity.
	â€¢	Text & Neutral: Text in light mode will be mostly dark gray or near-black for readability. For instance, main body text #2A2A2A (a charcoal) instead of true black, to keep the soft feel. Headings could be black or very close to it (#000 or #111). Secondary text can be mid-gray (#6F6F6F). Borders and divider lines might use a light gray (#DADADA). We still incorporate the brand colors in icons or emphasis text where appropriate, but most of the canvas in light mode is neutral and open.
	â€¢	Semantic Colors:
	â€¢	Success: a green that is friendly (e.g., #29B378, mindful of contrast on light â€“ that might need dark text on it, etc.).
	â€¢	Warning: an amber/yellow that is not too light to fade (maybe #EBAE17).
	â€¢	Error: a slightly deeper red for light bg (#D94A4A).
	â€¢	Info: the blue itself.
These should align with or be direct conversions of the dark palette choices, just tweaked for context (for example, the same hex might work if we use dark text on it). Maintain consistent meaning of colors across modes to avoid confusion.
	â€¢	Overall Feel: Light mode should feel airy, spacious, and calm â€“ like a cloudy morning with a bit of colorful sunrise. We avoid stark contrasts (except where needed for text). We can use soft shadows for depth (e.g., a card might have a very subtle shadow to lift it, color #000 with maybe 5% opacity blur for a gentle effect). Gradients on light might be used in illustrations, but likely the UI itself stays mostly flat colors (with maybe a header or hero having a pale gradient). If using a gradient background in a hero section on light, something like a pale blue to pale purple pastel gradient could be nice, but very low-key.

Palette Usage & Accessibility: Designers should stick to the core palette and avoid randomly picking new colors. If variety is needed, derive from these primaries (e.g., lighter tints, darker shades). Ensure sufficient contrast for text/icons: for instance, avoid placing our bright blue text on a white background unless the blue is darkened to meet AA contrast. Use the official dark and light theme values provided once theyâ€™re tested. In general, lean on the dark background with light text format (or vice versa) for any important copy so itâ€™s highly legible. The colorful accents should complement, not impede readability (use them for buttons, highlights, small areas). Keep in mind color-blind accessibility â€“ e.g., differentiate error (red) and success (green/amber) with icons or labels, not color alone. We want Ori to be as inclusive visually as it is in voice.

(Tip: When presenting the palette, show swatches with their HEX codes and an example usage for each â€“ e.g., background, primary button, link text, etc., so developers and future designers apply them consistently. Also provide an example of both modes side by side to illustrate consistency.)

Typography

A clear and characterful typography system will further express Oriâ€™s brand. We want type that is modern (for tech cred), highly legible (for UI), yet with a human touch (not overly mechanical).

Primary Typeface: A geometric sans-serif for headlines and UI, complemented by a humanist typeface for body text. For example, we might use Circular or Google Sans (Product Sans) for headings â€“ these fonts have clean round shapes (the â€œOâ€ is a perfect circle, which echoes Oriâ€™s orb motif) and a friendly vibe. They exude modernity and approachability. For body copy and dense text, a humanist sans like Inter, Roboto, or Helvetica Neue (or a similar open-source font) works well â€“ these are designed for legibility at small sizes and have more neutral, warm proportions. The pairing ensures the look is neither too whimsical nor too formal.

All typography should be web-friendly and available for both web and mobile app (Google Fonts or similar for ease, if needed, or a licensed font built into the design system).
	â€¢	Headings: Use the geometric sans at distinct weights for hierarchy. Perhaps H1 (hero or page titles) is Bold or Semi-Bold, with a comfortable letter spacing (geometric sans tend to look great in bold at large sizes). H2, H3 can be Medium weight. Emphasize sentence case (avoid all-caps for large headings to keep the calm tone, unless a particular design calls for it sparingly). The headings can have a bit of extra spacing (like 1.05x normal) to give an airy feel. Example: â€œOri Guides Youâ€ as a section title in 36px, bold, nearly black (or white on dark). This stands out but with rounded letters, it wonâ€™t feel shouting.
	â€¢	Body Text: For most paragraphs and descriptions, use the humanist sans (or if the chosen primary font is very legible, could use one font for all but with varying weights). Body text should be Regular weight, 16px or so for web default (adjust for device). It should be black on light mode, or white on dark mode, at high contrast for readability. The humanist typeface will have slightly softer curves and more variation in stroke, making reading longer text comfortable. We might also allow a serif font for any long-form articles or blog content if needed to differentiate content type â€“ but the product UI itself likely wonâ€™t need a serif. If a serif is desired for an editorial touch, something like Georgia or Charter in small doses could work, but this is optional.
	â€¢	UI Text & Labels: Many UI components (buttons, input placeholders, tooltips) will use the sans-serif as well. We should define sizes: e.g., Button text uppercase or Title Case in Medium weight, slightly smaller (14px maybe) but with good letter spacing for clarity. Form labels maybe small (12-14px) in Medium or Uppercase with a neutral color. Make sure even the small text has sufficient contrast (e.g., placeholder text in dark mode might be #888888 which on #121212 is just around the acceptable range, maybe lighten it a bit).
	â€¢	Special Typography: If the brand wants to emphasize the tech angle for code or algorithm references, we can include a monospace font (like JetBrains Mono or Courier New for a classic choice) to use in moderation (e.g., in a graphic, or to style something Ori â€œwritesâ€ like pseudocode for your career plan â€“ only if it fits a concept). But generally, monospace wonâ€™t be core to the brand voice since weâ€™re focusing on human tone, not hardcore coding aesthetic.
	â€¢	Tone in Typography: Use italics or bold sparingly for emphasis in copy â€“ Oriâ€™s voice doesnâ€™t shout, so bold is used for maybe titles or key numbers, not for random emphasis. We might use italic to denote a thoughtful or hypothetical tone (as we did in samples with stars or â€œfulfillmentâ€). Underlines only for actual links. Avoid aggressive ALL-CAPS except perhaps on small UI elements like button labels if design prefers (though Title Case or sentence case on buttons feels more aligned with Oriâ€™s calmness, e.g., â€œContinueâ€ vs â€œCONTINUEâ€).
	â€¢	Scale & Modularity: The type scale should probably follow a modular scale for consistency (e.g., each heading size maybe 1.25x larger than the previous). Ensure line-heights are generous, especially in light mode (maybe 1.6 for body text) to enhance that spacious, calm feel. In dark mode, a slightly tighter line-height (1.5) might appear more cohesive given white text on black can halo a bit.

(Design tip: Put together a typography style guide page: show H1 through H6, body text, captions, and an example of form text, to ensure consistency. Include examples of the type in use with the actual brand copy if possible, so the mood is clear. The chosen fonts should reflect the brand keywords â€“ serene (so no harsh blocky font), intuitive (readable), whimsical (a touch of playfulness, maybe in the geometric O or in a nice ampersand etc.).)

Imagery & Illustration Style

Our imagery will mix cosmic wonder, natural warmth, and human relatability. We want to visualize the concept of â€œguiding lightâ€ and continuous growth without resorting to clichÃ© stock photos of people shaking hands. The style will be primarily illustrative with abstract elements, possibly supplemented by very carefully chosen photographic textures for richness (e.g., a real night sky or soft bokeh lights, blended subtly â€“ but illustrations lead the way).

Key characteristics of Oriâ€™s imagery style:
	â€¢	People Depiction: When showing humans or characters, opt for simplified, stylized figures rather than detailed realistic photographs. This could mean silhouettes or minimal line-and-shape illustrations of people. For inclusivity, if we illustrate a person, avoid specific facial details or skin tones that anchor to one ethnicity â€“ use more universal representations (e.g., two-tone illustrative people, or people drawn as outlines with a galaxy inside them, etc.). Another approach: depict the idea of a person via their outline filled with a gradient or starfield. If at times stock photography is used (say for blog posts), it should be photos that feel candid, calm, and optimistic â€“ and likely overlaid with a slight color tint or Oriâ€™s gradient to maintain brand feel. But primarily, we anticipate using illustrations and possibly 3D rendered scenes for a futuristic touch.
	â€¢	Space + Nature Fusion: Imagery should frequently include elements like stars, constellations, planets, or cosmic swirls combined with natural motifs like plants, mountains, or the glow of fireflies. For example, an illustration might show a silhouette of a person looking up at a constellation that subtly outlines a career ladder or a path â€“ blending the idea of aspiration (stars) with guidance (constellation forming a shape). Another might show a tiny Ori firefly guiding a person through a dark forest, where the darkness is filled with gentle patterns of circuit-like constellations. The color palette for illustrations will use our brand colors: dark blues, purples, with pops of white and blue for stars, and warm amber for any natural light (like a lantern or the firefly).
	â€¢	Use of Glow and Light: Embrace glow effects to create the feeling of bioluminescence and technology magic. Techniques could include: soft halos around Ori mascot, glowing particles in the background (like firefly lights or stars), gradient glows behind key text or UI elements for emphasis. However, keep glows soft and diffuse (no sharp neon glints that would feel harsh). Motion blur or glow streaks could imply movement of the mascot or progress in an illustration (e.g., a streak of light following a path to indicate travel). Glows can also highlight specific content sections (like a call-out quote might have a subtle background glow graphic).
	â€¢	Level of Realism: Lean towards semi-abstract and symbolic rather than literal realism. That means we often illustrate concepts metaphorically. Example: to depict â€œcontinuous evolution of oneâ€™s professional identity,â€ an image might show a series of butterfly-like icons (but robotic or starry) emerging upward, or a personâ€™s silhouette with layers peeling into new silhouettes, guided by Oriâ€™s light. These are abstract representations of ideas. Photographic realism is not the goal; if photos are used, they will likely be overlaid or integrated into a design that also has illustration (mixed media style) to keep consistency. The overall impression should be somewhat dreamy and imaginative, yet clean â€“ akin to looking at a thoughtfully designed sci-fi book cover or a calm animation still.
	â€¢	Illustration Style: We can choose between a vector flat style with gradients (for a modern SaaS feel) or a subtle 3D style (using tools like Blender or Cinema4D to create soft, round 3D shapes for Ori and environment). A hybrid could work: perhaps Ori the mascot is a 3D render for extra smoothness and lighting, while backgrounds are flat vectors with gradient fills. If going pure vector, use smooth lines, generous curves, and avoid clutter. If going for 3D, keep materials matte or softly glowing â€“ nothing too shiny or textured heavily. In either case, maintain a consistent stroke or shape language. Possibly incorporate circular motif (circles, orbits) since Ori is about cycles and guidance.
	â€¢	Gradients and Abstract Shapes: Gradients should mimic natural phenomena like dusk skies or auroras: e.g., a gradient that goes from deep blue to teal to purple might serve as a background. Abstract shapes like swirling lines (to indicate connection or paths), dots (stars), and gentle curves (orbits, wave patterns) can be used as decorative elements. For instance, a background pattern on the website could be a faint array of dots and lines like a constellation map. Or on a slide, a corner might have a fade of color with a few sparkles. Consistency here is key â€“ pick a motif (like constellations or glow orbits) and use it subtly across various materials.
	â€¢	Iconography: Icons in the product should align with the illustration style â€“ likely line icons or filled icons with rounded corners. They should use the same stroke width and style across the set. Prefer metaphoric icons when possible (e.g., a small spark icon for â€œinsightâ€, a target icon for â€œgoalâ€, etc.) to stay on theme. Use the primary accent colors for icons where color is needed, otherwise neutrals. Avoid overly detailed icon designs; keep them minimal and intuitive.
	â€¢	Imagery in Motion (for later, if animated): While static guidelines are our focus, hint at how things could move. E.g., an animation of Ori flitting around leaving a trail of light, or stars slowly twinkling in a hero section. Static designs can imply these by showing multiple positions of a moving element in a single graphic (motion lines). When we do animate in product or marketing, the motion should be slow, easing, and calming (no hectic flashing).

In summary, Oriâ€™s visual world should feel like stepping into a calm night illuminated by friendly starlight and the gentle pulse of fireflies â€“ where high-tech data (constellations, networks) merges with the organic (nature, personal human journey). Every visual element, from the mascot to the color of a button, should reinforce that Ori is quietly powerful, empathetic, and a bit magical. Designers should be able to take these guidelines and create anything from a landing page illustration to a social media graphic and have it immediately recognizable as Ori.

(Example prompt for hero illustration: â€œA young professional stands at a cosmic crossroads under a starry night sky. A small glowing robot-firefly (Ori) hovers beside them, casting a soft light on one path. The scene is minimalist, with silhouettes of mountains and a few plants at their feet, and constellations in the sky subtly forming shapes of different career icons.â€ This kind of imagery would capture the brandâ€™s essence.)

Product & UX/UI Guidance

Translating the brand into the product experience is crucial. Oriâ€™s UX/UI should embody the brand personality â€” meaning using the visual elements and voice in a way that makes the app feel like interacting with that calm, whimsical, intuitive guide. Below we outline how the brand informs various aspects of product design:

Layout & Navigation Personality

The overall layout should communicate clarity, calm, and guidance. We want users to feel oriented (no pun intended) and not overwhelmed when using Ori.
	â€¢	Homepage (Marketing Site): The homepage should immediately convey spaciousness and focus. Use ample negative space, especially in dark mode with perhaps a starry subtle background. The hero section might have a headline, subheadline, CTA, and an illustration (Ori mascot guiding a user) â€“ all centered and balanced. Use a grid system to align sections, but break the grid creatively with imagery (for a whimsical touch, maybe an illustration overlaps two sections slightly, or a diagonal shape divides sections mimicking a horizon). Each scroll section should have one key message and maybe an accompanying visual, rather than dense text. The color scheme here can showcase the dark cosmic palette with bright accent pops on CTAs (e.g., a spectral blue â€œGet Startedâ€ button on a dark hero). As the user scrolls, the guide (Ori) can appear in images or as a little motif pointing out things (â€œOri tip: â€¦â€ kind of elements in the design). Importantly, the homepage should not feel like a cookie-cutter SaaS template â€“ our brand elements (mascot, gradients, stars) should give it a unique flavor that matches our ethos of guiding light and continuous growth.
	â€¢	Dashboard (Authenticated App): Once in the app, the dashboard is like a home base for the userâ€™s career journey. This should feel intuitive and personalized. Likely a two-column or card-based layout where Ori highlights the most important information first (e.g., one card might say â€œYour Progress this weekâ€ with a friendly summary, another â€œNew Opportunities for Youâ€ listing a couple of roles, etc.). The navigation (perhaps a sidebar or top menu) should use clear icons+labels (e.g., Home, Jobs, Skills, Messages, Profile). Given our brand, using icons with rounded style and maybe the accent color for the active state is good. The vibe of the dashboard is calm â€“ not a million blinking notifications. We use visual hierarchy (large headings and key stats) to draw attention rather than bright red badges everywhere. Oriâ€™s mascot might appear in a small welcome message up top: e.g., a little Ori icon next to text â€œGood evening, [Name]. Ready for your next step?â€ This immediately personalizes the experience. The layout should adapt between dark and light modes gracefully (maybe user can choose mode or itâ€™s by system default).
	â€¢	Overall Layout Considerations: Keep a consistent spacing scale â€“ padding and margins that give enough breathing room (e.g., 16px or 24px base grid). Use card surfaces or section backgrounds to group related content, but avoid heavy boxing of everything (which can feel cluttered). Instead, rely on spacing and subtle dividers or different background tones to separate sections. The navigation and header should be unobtrusive â€“ perhaps a slim top bar with the Ori logo on left and maybe user avatar on right. In dark mode, that bar could be nearly black or translucent. In light mode, it could be white with a bottom border. The brandâ€™s whimsical touches (like a tiny star icon as a bullet point or the firefly appearing next to a section title) can be sprinkled in, but should not disrupt functionality â€“ always secondary to usability.

UI Elements: Buttons, Cards, Inputs, Icons

All UI components should reflect Oriâ€™s design principles: approachable (rounded where possible), high-contrast and accessible, and subtly lively (with small animations or interactive feedback that feel â€œaliveâ€).
	â€¢	Buttons: Use the primary accent color (electric blue or spectral blue) for primary action buttons. Buttons should have moderately rounded corners (e.g., 6px or even fully pill-shaped if that fits the style). The text on them should be clear (use the chosen font, Medium weight). For dark mode, a bright blue button with white text works, and on hover or focus, consider adding an outer glow or a slight pulse animation to reinforce the guiding light feel. In light mode, a filled blue button also works (with maybe a slightly darker hover), or one can use a ghost style (blue border, white fill) for secondary actions. Ensure button height is comfortable (not tiny) â€“ since Ori is about guidance, we donâ€™t want fiddly small tap targets. Maybe 44px height min, with extra padding for a friendly feel. The button label tone should be action-oriented but gentle (â€œView Detailsâ€ or â€œExplore rolesâ€ vs. just â€œSubmitâ€).
	â€¢	Cards/ Panels: Use card layouts to encapsulate things like job suggestions, skill progress, etc. Cards can have a slight background color (in dark mode, maybe a slightly lighter dark #1E2A38 panel on #0D1B2A background; in light mode, white panel on light gray background). Give them rounded corners (consistent with buttons, say 6px or 8px radius) to match the friendly aesthetic. Add a small drop shadow or elevation especially in light mode (very soft shadow) and perhaps a faint glow in dark mode (like a subtle neon edge) to make them distinct. Each card might have an icon or small graphic â€“ ensure those icons use brand colors or illustrations that include Ori if appropriate (like Ori peeking on an empty-state card). Spacing inside cards should be generous (no wall of text). If listing items (like a list of jobs), separate them with subtle dividers or distinct sub-cards so itâ€™s not overwhelming.
	â€¢	Inputs & Forms: Input fields (text boxes, dropdowns) should be minimal and clean. Use rounded rectangle borders (again a small radius to tie together with buttons and cards). In dark mode, perhaps the input has a border or background of #273544 (dark grey) and a slight inner glow on focus. In light mode, a white input with a solid border #CCC that turns to the blue accent on focus is good. Placeholder text, as mentioned in typography, should be in a friendly tone if needed (e.g., a search box could say â€œSearch roles or skillsâ€¦â€ rather than just â€œSearchâ€). Include accessible labels or helper text that follows Oriâ€™s voice (â€œChoose 3 skills youâ€™d love to develop â€“ this helps me tailor suggestions.â€ would be a nice helper line near a multiselect input). For interactive controls like sliders or toggle switches, incorporate the accent colors (a toggle switch might be a small pill toggle that glows blue when â€œonâ€, etc.).
	â€¢	Icons: Icons throughout the UI should be consistent style â€“ likely line icons with a slight round line cap, or simple filled icons. Use a stroke width that is legible (maybe 1.5px at 24px size for line icons). Common icons might include: a compass or map pin (for navigation or career path concept), a star (for favorites or something notable), a book or graduation cap (learning), a briefcase (job roles), a chat bubble (messages), etc. All icons should be derived from a common set or library and then tweaked to match Oriâ€™s style (rounded corners, etc.). Use the brandâ€™s primary colors appropriately: for instance, the active nav icon could be highlighted in the blue; notifications icon might use the amber for a dot, etc. But avoid a multicolor rainbow of icons in one screen â€“ better to use mostly neutral or monochrome icons and just accent the ones needing attention. If an icon can incorporate a slight whimsical element, go for it (e.g., maybe the â€œopportunityâ€ icon is a small shooting star rather than a generic bell). But clarity comes first â€“ users should immediately recognize what an icon means.
	â€¢	Corner Radius Philosophy: Weâ€™ve touched on corners: basically, nothing in Oriâ€™s UI should have painfully sharp edges. The general radius in the design system might be ~8px for main components (buttons, cards), perhaps larger (16px) for very large surfaces like a modal window to really soften it. However, we also avoid going full â€œbubblyâ€ unless it suits â€“ balance soft with modern. The radius chosen should carry across consistently so the UI feels cohesive.
	â€¢	Shadows and Depth: Oriâ€™s design likely uses depth sparingly to keep it calm. In dark mode, traditional drop shadows donâ€™t show much; instead, we might use glows or lighter panel colors for layering. In light mode, use subtle shadows to differentiate layers (like a floating card over background). The philosophy: shadows/glows are functional (to show hierarchy) but can also reinforce the brand (a glow = Oriâ€™s guiding light metaphor). E.g., perhaps the currently highlighted section gets a very faint pulsing glow behind it to draw the eye. But be careful not to overdo animations (only for important states).
	â€¢	Motion / Micro-interactions: (Integrating here although there is a separate motion section below, since it ties to elements.) Buttons might slightly animate on click â€“ e.g., a quick subtle glow or a depress effect. Icons could have hover animations (maybe the star icon twinkles when hovered, etc.). These little touches make the UI feel alive and in tune with the mascot character.

Motion Design: How Ori Appears & Interacts

Oriâ€™s motion design should be gentle, meaningful, and delightful without being distracting. Think of Ori not just as graphics on a screen, but as something with behaviors.
	â€¢	Mascot Appearances: Ori (the mascot) could appear contextually with simple animations. For example, when the app loads, instead of a generic spinner, you might see a tiny Ori firefly icon looping or fluttering softly â€“ essentially a custom loading animation that doubles as branding. When Ori presents a tip or message (like in a tutorial overlay), the mascot icon could fade in with a slight upward float and glow, as if it â€œflew inâ€ quietly. These movements should be slow-ish and easing (no bouncy rapid motions, which would feel too hyper for our serene vibe). Ori might also have an idle animation in certain screens â€“ e.g., on a mostly static dashboard, a tiny Ori in the corner could blink or gently sway once in a long while, to give a sense of a living presence, but it should be very minimal so as not to steal focus.
	â€¢	General UI Transitions: Transitions between pages or states (like moving from the dashboard to a detailed role view) should be smooth and calming. Perhaps use a fade-in/out combined with a slight slide. Avoid harsh instant changes or jarring effects. A nice touch: incorporate dissolve to black or dissolve through light transitions (mimicking eyes opening/closing) when appropriate. For instance, if there is a major mode switch, maybe the screen does a quick fade through a color (like a flash of blue or a brief dimming like a blink). Keep durations moderate (300ms to 500ms for most, maybe a tad longer for very significant transitions like finishing onboarding to first dashboard, to create a moment of â€œwelcomeâ€).
	â€¢	Hover and Feedback States: For interactive elements, provide feedback that aligns with the theme. Hover on a card might subtly raise it (as if levitating) and add a slight glow at its edges. Clicking a button might produce a ripple or a quick glow that then fades. If using Material-like ripple, maybe make it a glow ripple rather than a harsh solid one. Focus states (for keyboard navigation) should be clearly indicated with outlines or glows in the accent color so accessibility is strong.
	â€¢	Micro-interactions with Meaning: Use small animations to celebrate or acknowledge user actions. E.g., when a user marks a goal as achieved, you could trigger a tiny burst of star particles or a brief trail of light that moves upward â€“ a visual â€œhigh fiveâ€ from Ori. When a user completes onboarding, maybe Ori does a little loop-de-loop animation with a shine. Conversely, when something is loading or thinking, Ori might rotate slowly or a small orbit animation can show â€œIâ€™m working on itâ€ â€“ better than just a spinner. All these should be optional subtle cues; nothing should trap the user or waste time, they should always be able to proceed.
	â€¢	Avoiding Distraction: While we have these nice motions, remember many users will be using Ori seriously to plan careers â€“ we must not annoy them. So animations should generally only play once at significant moments (not on every minor interaction repeatedly). Provide settings if needed to reduce motion for those who prefer it (honoring â€œprefers-reduced-motionâ€ CSS for example). The key is to strike delight, not gimmick. Oriâ€™s motions are like its way of speaking non-verbally: gentle nods, not frantic gestures.

Empty States & Onboarding with Ori as Guide

We touched on empty states in copy and visuals, hereâ€™s a strategic take on them:
	â€¢	Empty States Philosophy: An empty state (when a section has no data yet) is not just a blank â€“ itâ€™s an opportunity to a) reassure the user and b) guide them towards the next step. Oriâ€™s mascot should often appear in these scenarios to personify that reassurance. The design of an empty state could feature a smaller illustration or icon of Ori plus a short message in Oriâ€™s voice (see copy example). For consistency, possibly design a standard empty state component: e.g., an illustrated Ori sitting on a file cabinet for an empty â€œSaved jobsâ€ list, or Ori holding a compass for an empty â€œCareer planâ€. Use the brand colors (some light background shape, plus the illustration). Keep it visually lightweight â€“ not too many elements â€“ to keep focus on what the user should do next. And always include a call-to-action or tip (â€œUse the search to add your first goal,â€ etc.).
	â€¢	Onboarding Flow: The onboarding of Ori (first-run experience) should feel like meeting your guide. Instead of a dry form, consider a conversational onboarding: Ori might â€œaskâ€ the user questions one by one (simulating a chat or interactive form, even if itâ€™s just a multi-step form UI with the mascot icon next to each question). For example, step 1: â€œHi, Iâ€™m Ori! To help you best, Iâ€™d love to know a bit about you. First, whatâ€™s a goal you have in your career?â€ with an input. Step 2: â€œThanks! And which fields or industries excite you?â€ etc. The UI for this could show Oriâ€™s mascot on one side of the screen, with speech bubbles or cards containing these questions, and answer fields below. This makes it feel less like â€œfill this formâ€ and more like a friendly interview. Use progress indicators (like a series of dots or steps at the top) with possibly little playful labels (â€œHelloâ€, â€œSkillsâ€, â€œDreamsâ€, â€œFinishâ€) to orient without stress.
	â€¢	Oriâ€™s Presence in Guidance (not distraction): We emphasize that Ori-as-mascot should help, not annoy like a certain infamous paperclip. To achieve this, make Oriâ€™s interventions contextual and user-controlled. For instance, have a â€œNeed help?â€ floating Ori icon that the user can click if they want guidance on the page. Or a subtle pulse on the Ori icon if it has something to say (and if user ignores it, it quiets down). In tutorials, allow skipping. Ori should never cover important content or pop up randomly with off-topic tips. One idea: a persistent but discrete â€œOri barâ€ or sidebar section in the dashboard where Oriâ€™s latest tip or question is. Itâ€™s part of the layout rather than an overlay, so the user can engage when ready.
	â€¢	Examples of Onboarding Visuals: Possibly include a hero illustration on the sign-up screen: a user silhouette and Ori greeting them. Then use simpler illustrations or just the mascot head for subsequent steps. Each screenâ€™s visuals and text should reinforce positivity (â€œWeâ€™re excited to have youâ€, â€œThis info helps me help youâ€). At the end of onboarding, do a brief celebratory screen â€“ Ori might appear with a slightly larger graphic saying â€œWelcome aboard, [Name]!â€ maybe with a tagline about moving forward. That moment should segue into the actual app with a smooth transition (perhaps Ori literally â€œguidesâ€ them by pointing to where to start).
	â€¢	Guided Tips in UI: Once onboarded, Ori might occasionally highlight new features or sections with a one-time tooltip (with the mascot icon) that says e.g., â€œThis is your Weekly Outlook â€“ Iâ€™ll update it every Friday with new insights.â€ These should be few and well-timed (perhaps tied to triggers like first visit of a section or after a week of usage). They should also be easily dismissible. The visual style can be a small dark or light tooltip box with the Ori icon next to it and an arrow pointing to the element. This ensures continuity of the guiding persona even as user explores.

In essence, the product should feel like Ori-the-character is woven into it â€” not in an overbearing way, but as a helpful presence embedded in the UI and UX writing. By aligning layout, components, and interactive behavior with the brandâ€™s calm and guiding ethos, we ensure users experience the brand values directly whenever they use Ori.

(Design idea: The empty state illustrations and onboarding graphics can double as content for social or help docs, creating a coherent visual story. For example, the image of Ori guiding a person up a path used in onboarding can appear in a blog post about â€œfinding your pathâ€. This cross-use reinforces the brand consistently.)

